example.p:
If we fold a sheet of letter paper in half, the visible surface area is
\frac{\SI{93.52}{\square\inch}}{2} & =\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\SI{93.5}{\square\inch} & =\SI{46.75}{\square\inch}
Note that we say, visible, because the actual surface area of the paper has not changed.

If we fold the sheet in half again, the visible surface area is
\frac{\SI{46.75}{\square\inch}}{2} & = \frac{\SI{93.52}{\square\inch}}{4} & = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2\SI{93.5}{\square\inch} & \approx \SI{23.38}{\square\inch}
If we fold the sheet in half a third time, the visible surface area is
\frac{\SI{93.5}{\square\inch}}{8} & = \left( \frac{1}{2}\right)^3\SI{93.5}{\square\inch} & \approx \SI{11.69}{\square\inch}

